The great macroeconomic divergence
PARIS – "The global expansion has reached its peak" warns the OECD in its latest economic outlook and performance may suffer if downward risks occur.
The party is not over yet: it is reckoned that global growth will continue in 2019 and 2020 – albeit at a slower pace.
However, economists are notoriously bad at recognizing macroeconomic turning points and the future economic course is difficult to assess.
There are numerous possible stumbling blocks: the more aggressive monetary tightening, especially in the United States; a further escalation of protectionism; a harder-than-expected economic landing in China; and a return of tensions in the Eurozone, triggered by concerns regarding the fate of Italian state finances.
All that or each of these developments could strengthen the downturn that has already begun.
A recession in the US would be frustrating for President Donald Trump, who is already looking forward to his re-election in 2020, but such a development would not contradict known patterns.
The expansion officially began in June 2009 and with a duration until July 2019, it would be the longest such phase in the economic history of the US.
The unemployment rate is at its lowest level since the 1960s.
Under these conditions, the implementation of the economic policies of the Trump administration consisting of massive tax cuts and increased expenditure – thus a stimulus package comparable to that of 2009, which was intended to avert a threatening depression – is economically not sensible.
Thus, the Federal Reserve has only two options left: either it drastically raises interest rates to offset the poorly timed economic measures or it surrenders.
A play of irresponsibility and cowardice between the US budget and monetary authorities in the face of the global impact of the US interest cycle increases the risk of instability worldwide.
A global recession would come too early for those countries whose recovery was delayed or weak or both.
A extreme example is Greece, where the growth picked up only in 2017 and unemployment is still almost 20 percent.
But Greece is not alone.
In Italy, the per capita GDP is not higher than in the middle of the 1990s.
And in Spain, France, South Korea, and other countries, unemployment is still significantly above the pre-crisis level.
The challenge lies in re-employing long-term unemployed people, for whom the risk of qualification loss exists.
To avoid lasting socio-economic damage, these countries need faster growth.
A promising international situation alone cannot solve their problems, but it would help to maximize the benefits of national reforms.
The other extreme is presented by the German labor market, which is currently in a much better condition than in 2007.
In the western federal states, there is full employment, and economic growth is increasingly dependent on migration: in 2017, the net influx (not refugees, but immigrants from other European countries) was around 400,000 people.
In Japan, the UK, and Poland, the recovery was also characterized by the creation of many new jobs.
Citizens complain about income, inequality, or rising property prices, but not about a lack of jobs.
Ten years ago, the crisis hit almost all developed economies simultaneously.
Today, however, they do not appear neither structurally nor cyclically on one line.
This is quite alarming, because the impending cooling of the world economy comes at a time of increasing political fragility.
Trust in governments and institutions of political decision-making is – understandably – extremely low.
Collective economic mismanagement would only further undermine this trust and fuel the already rising economic nationalism.
What is to be done?
The list of tasks to be tackled begins at home. In many countries, where the labor market is still out of balance, national measures are needed to strengthen economic potential and improve access to jobs.
In France, employers report a shortage of skilled workers despite an unemployment rate of 9 percent and the reforms of President Emmanuel Macron.
To change that, comprehensive measures in the area of training are just as necessary as support for mobility, incentives for taking jobs and opening up protected sectors.
This is already happening.
In Italy, however, the ruling coalition has initiated a stimulus program and at the same time proposed measures to reduce labor market participation.
Examples of this include the repeal of the pension reform in 2011, as well as the introduction of a "citizen income," which, in the event of inadequate planning or implementation, will lead to fewer people pursuing employment.
This political inconsistency and Italy's deviation from the EU's budgetary rules is the true cause for concern.
The second priority is to establish a risk balance.
For a while now, a political debate has been unfolding between hawks and doves, with the former warning that the central banks' asset purchases and near-zero interest rates will fuel financial instability and inflation risks.
Both are, in fact, real, but there is more reason to be concerned about deflation.
Property price bubbles can be dampened by regulatory measures, such as capping the ratio between loan amounts and the value of the property or between loan amounts and income.
Projections on inflation are repeatedly refuted.
Wages have thus far reacted slowly to the declining unemployment rate.
There is a justified fear of a possible abrupt increase, but after so many years of undershooting inflation, one can take this risk.
The collective costs of a temporary inflation overshoot pale in comparison to those of an early onset recession, which leads to lasting damage and a political counter-movement against economic orthodoxy.
The third priority, international coordination, is far and away the most difficult to achieve, especially in the eurozone, where the European Central Bank pursues a uniform policy for different national economies.
The standard recipe would be for the ECB to target the average inflation rate and rely on national fiscal policy for fine-tuning the macroeconomic course.
However, due to higher debt or remaining deficits, it is precisely those countries that would need further growth that do not have any room for maneuver in their fiscal policy.
Neither Greece nor Italy, nor indeed Spain or France, can currently consider a substantial stimulus program.
Without the possibility of inter-state transfers (which are not even foreseen in the latest agreement between France and Germany on a mini-Eurozone budget) this is another reason why the ECB should be more courageous.
Leaving the task of cooling down their economies with fiscal policy to governments of countries threatened by overheating, while the task of developing their economic potential would fall to the governments of countries still struggling to improve their economy.
There are numerous reasons to doubt that this is possible.
But it is the task of policymakers to steer risks, even if the risks of today are not the usual ones.
The resilience of the global economic system is at stake.
Despite favorable conditions, the first cracks are starting to show.
It must be prevented from turning into cracks.
